Came here on a Friday night with a party of 3. We made reservations earlier that same day. We heard this place had a good burger and it was true, the double bacon cheeseburger was delicious. Very convenient location with excellent service, especially since we had two youngsters with us.  They accommodated us wonderfully and the FOOD gets better and better. Delicious!

Amazing food, absolutely one of my favorite restaurants in DC. The drinks are fantastic and reasonably priced. The French food is exquisite, probably because the owner is French. Definitely recommend for Brunch and Dinner.

Convivial is one of, if not our favorite, restaurant in D.C. We came here for our first date, and have been back many times since. Especially since it holds a special place! The food is always amazing and never disappoints. Cannot recommend it highly enough. You won't be disappointed.

Amazing food! Incredibly friendly service. John Ferris was our server and he made our night! The duck entree was decadent. Don’t leave without getting dessert.

Holy wow this place was amazing. Went for a restaurant week patio Covid dining experience and everything was incredible. Hand sanitizer and bug spray on the tables and good signage for masks and how to get to the restroom if need be inside  Every single course was fresh, warm, came quickly after each was finished and the servers were even accommodating through a brief rain storm that came through. We huddled under a patio umbrella and they brought us our dessert! Cannot say enough great things. Will be back soon! Everyone loved every single item. No complaints

Food and vibe was great. We brought our dog along and he was being more curious than usual, but everyone took it in stride. Servers and Bussers doing a wonderful job, and they had bug spray for guests that had inadvertently become dinner while eating dinner. I recommend the paella and mousse!

Chef Monpilier is creative, and produces consistently fine food, even now under these difficult circumstances. Who though of porridge for dinner? Yet I've had it three times, I like it so much. The chicken is always special, and the take home options are nicely prepared to travel. I can't wait to enjoy the food in the restaurant again. It was my mother-in-law's choice for her 90th birthday dinner.

I was completely blown away by the dinner I had at Convivial. I went for restaurant week where I got a three course meal for a more than reasonable price ($35). The food was incredible and you can tell they put effort into every little detail (they even offered hand sanitizer and bug spray on the tables). The staff is very attentive and I most definitely plan on going back soon. If you are looking for a safe place to dine during the pandemic that also has good food, check this place out!

Convivial is really fine dining. I had a delicious lunch there before covid. The Washington Post food critic, Tom Sietsema, continuously raves about it and for good reason. We had takeout yesterday. The gazpacho is one of the best we've ever had and the salmon and fixings and the summer vegetable and quinoa porridge were very special. The chocolate mousse is silky smooth, rich and luscious. Can't wait to try other dishes.
The food here is has always excelled and am very glad to report that nothing has changed.

I’ve ordered from their daily menu for two almost every week since the lockdown started and continue to be blown away by how good value it is. The portions are so big they are easily enough for two meals for me and my partner. And it’s delicious too. I thoroughly recommend the sticky toffee pudding.

We ordered the carry out Lamb, Endive Salad, Key Lime pie and olives. Baguette came with the order and it was INCREDIBLE bread!  Amazing value, the ‘serves 2’ served 3 of us easily. Thanks for staying open so that we could try your food!
Amazing food. Mind blowing cinnamon rolls!

We did takeout from Convivial tonight. Absolutely awesome. Pickup went seemlessly. Wonderful coq au vin, onion soup, potato chips, and chocolate mousse. Did not suffer from the drive home. This has always been one of our favorite restaurants and we will comd back often while we’re staying home. I’d post a photo but we ate the food too fast.
First-rate vibes and very welcoming service. The food was crisp and delicious. Will surely recommend this spot to friends and family. Fair rates and big portions. Keep up the great work.

This place is packed so make a reservation and don't expect to be seated early. For the appetizers I HIGHLY recommend the burrata, I had never had a bell pepper carpaccio but it goes well with the fresh cheese. For the main course the steak, trout, and bouillabaisse are all quite tasty!

We went to Convivial for our Christmas eve dinner, and it was so fantastic that we made reservations on the spot for their New Year's day brunch. Convivial is french made to enjoy not to intimidate, you can expect from a classic french onion soup that makes you say oh wow!  to other delights like Cassoulete and Bouillabaisse rooted on superb classic flavors, yet lighted up with a contemporary touch that, at least for me, seems to let you enjoy these dishes much more. That is also the balance of their atmosphere, you can dress up for your date and the restaurant ambiance feels chic and elegant, if you are passing by from work, their bar is casual and welcoming (with excellent cocktails). Did I mention that service is on point, helpful and attentive. Being that it was 6 of us I could write quite the extensive review of almost every dish, but my hope is that whoever is reading this simply go to try for themselves, no matter the occasion you can't go wrong with Convivial.
Wonderful flavors.  Good wine.  Wait staff attentive, knowledgeable, unobtrusive.
I had lunch there today. Delicious food  and the plate was well planned.  The  cheese was exceptional! Polite and efficient server! Nice experience.

Had dinner last night with friends. Everybody LOVED the food. The appetizers were creative (snails in a blanket!) or very well made French classics (salade lyonnaise, with frisee salad, chunky bacon bits and a poached egg). Wide choice of entrees. My choucroute (sauerkraut with sausages and meats) was perfect, my wife loved the duck à l'orange and my friend was raving about his bavette steak with fries. For desert, the profiterolles and the "floating islands"  were delightful. Both French and American guests around  the  table thought this was the best French food they had in a while. The restaurant is very pleasant, modern with a beautiful bar. The service was attentive and the Chef came to recommend a few things on the menu. He is very nice and took the time to speak to us. By the way, as we were hesitating between two Cabernet-Franc bottles of wine, he recommended the less expensive one! Great choice!  Go to Convivial soon!

This is a hard one to place. Everything about it was average. The food was average, the service was average, and the ambiance was average. I didn’t dislike it but I didn’t love anything. I ordered the burger because the menu was a fixture of nothing appealing. Gnocchi, oysters, and sea stew accompanied with Burgers and vege medley. When the vegetable medley is your best dish there is a problem. The burger was decent as was the medley. The bartender was an amazing guy and made a solid drink. The issue is not with him but the fact the bar was full and there was only one bartender to tend to it. I would say this is more of a Wednesday night dinner if you are in the neighborhood but not worth wasting a weekend over.

We ate here on a Sunday early evening with a large party including a younger child.  The service was very friendly and accommodating.   The menu was varied with many intersting options and a mix of new and traditional French dishes.  Food was very well prepared with interesting flavor combinations.   We recommend the chickpea fries for their texture and interesting concept, and the trout and Dourade for skillful preparation.   Overall a great meal and friendly ambience.  Hope to return soon.
Whether coming for dinner or brunch, with a group or for two, this is a great local spot. One of three best restaurants in Shaw.

Convivial offers a spacious environment of joyous people. Our waiter offered the best of the menu from the foie gras, roasted cauliflower, to the duck, daurade, steak, and gnocchi- every dish was unique and flavorful. For dessert, I would suggest ordering two of the sticky toffee. P.S: They have firecracker candles for birthday celebrations!

Good service and nice space but food is terrible. It’s a total gimmick. Interesting presentations but flavors are flat and uninspiring.  Combinations just don’t go well together. Masterfully juicy fried chicken sandwich bursting with flavor and goodness. Fries were okay.

As someone who has the Celiac disease, the dining out experience can sometimes be tricky for me. I always have to scrutinize the menu, and make sure that whatever I order should not contain a single molecule of gluten. Convivial has a separate gluten-free menu with a lot of healthy and flavorful options. I ordered the trout and it was delicious I even had a great gluten-free dessert called the floating island.

One of the best happy hours in town, a good fit for an afterwork spot, multiple options, great food and reasonable prices. They also have an extensive cocktails list (not on happy hour :-/ ), the bartender made us a delicious cocktail with bourbon, lemon and honey.

I took my visiting father out yesterday for father's day brunch to Convivial and the experience was beyond our expectations. Everything was great from the food to the service to the atmosphere, we both ordered the fried chicken and waffle and freshly squeezed juices. Everything was freshly made and the chicken was crispy, juicy and well seasoned with just the right amount of fat. I would recommend that you order the gravy on the side though.

I am so glad to find this hidden gem in shaw, this is the best french food I had in DC so far! Although the portions were not gigantic, I savored every bit of the pickled rockfish and the bouillabaisse that I ordered. Also they have a great choice of cocktails and wines. The overall experience was excellent and I am definitely going back there to try the rest of their menu.
Really delicious and varied food. Slightly small portions so share a lot.

My family and I drove in from NYC specifically to have brunch at Convival. Our waitress Miriam avoided our table and provided spotty, inconsistent service to our table. Once we left the restaurant we heard heavy, hostile, and racing footsteps traveling behind us. Miriam, the waitress, ran down the street to our car and asked why she did not receive a tip. My mother explained to Miriam that she felt her service was inadequate. When presented with a tip Miriam proceeded to forcefully snatch the money from my family member's hand and ran off without saying thank you. The nerve of Miriam to behave that way to paying customers.
Excellent food. Could use more vegetarian options.
The food here is no joke some of the best prepared food I’ve had. 10/10 would recommend.

Long overdue review of what has become my favorite restaurant in DC. I come down to DC every few months for business and make it a point to try to visit Convivial as much as my schedule allows. The atmosphere is warm, inviting, and relaxing. The food is out of this world delicious. It is complex without being pretentious and the breadth of the menu satisfies my cravings for rich, light, savory, or sweet depending on my mood. Chef Cedric has been at the restaurant on nearly every one of my visits and seems to make it a point to say hello to diners. I can't recommend Convivial enough
Lovely small plates with big price tags.
Everything was good. Service was perfectly attentive, no more no less. Chicken and waffles were a winner. Omelette and shrimp&grits were quite nice.

The atmosphere is fun and lively, great place for a celebratory dinner, dinner with friends or a date spot. The menu was a little limited but the food was delicious and everything came out looking beautiful (loved the presentation). They did have some vegetarian options! Our server was friendly. All around a good experience!
Just my kind of restaurant. Comfortable and tasty food without pretentiousness.

Delicious food,  pricey but worth it. In trendy petworth area
And amazingly great restaurant great food and amazing great service😀

Skip. I've been twice - once for dinner during restaurant week and once for brunch. The food is plated nicely, but the tastes fall flat. At brunch I had a $16 quiche lorraine neatly presented as a long, thin rectangle over a bed of well-dressed greens. Pretty. But it was both slippery (undercooked egg) and chewy (undercooked meat), with a flavorless crust. Ew. Also the latte I ordered was undrinkable -- old coffee mixed with lukewarm milk. Service was good for dinner, terrible at brunch. Relative to other restaurants with similar price-points, meals at Convivial have been among the worst.
Excellent food and service. Why hasn't Michelin given this place a 🌟 yet?
Great plates for happy hour. Cauliflower, duck gizzards and lamb sausage all fantastic.
When you want delicious food cuz you're a princess, or prince, eat here.

I have been here for restaurant week and for cocktails. It is almost always a pleasent experience. However, I did come one time and two of the people who I ate with got severe food poisoning the next day. That has unfortunately tainted my opinion of eating here again.

Good and unique dishes, I love how they use snakehead fish for the appetizers. Most of the food was delicious, especially the beef tartare and the roasted cauliflower, but my duck was a little tough to chew (tasty though). Staff was friendly and bubbly.
Love this place. Delicious, creative small plates and great Happy Hour.
Good brunch! Shrimp grits and English breakfast!

The staff was a little odd but the food and atmosphrere was wonderful. The lighting and music both compliment the environment well. The menu had a great layout and it was a good mix of comfort and modern dishes. Quality of the food was fantastic and the portions were a perfect size to fill you up without you feeling like you were gonna burst.
Food was a bit heavy handed. Nothing was terrible or inedible. Just not anything  that I am dying to eat again. Not sure I'd return.
Excellent chef. Blending if traditional and Nouveau Cuisine. A MUST visit.

Usually I'm not that into dessert, but the hot sticky toffee pudding with maple ice cream was divine! Since I was there for restaurant week with a few friends, we shared a bunch of the small plates, which were all beautifully presented and yummy. The bread was also extremely chewy and delightful. My main was the bouillabaisse with crusty bread, which I thoroughly enjoyed. Our server was lovely and knowledgeable about the wine we ordered. Overall, a great experience.

Food was decent but I was actually a little disappointed. The coq au Vin bites had, I dare say, too much bacon so it almost had a soy/Asian taste. The steak tartare had too much mustard, it masked the rest of the flavors.

Came during restaurant week, during which they had several options from their standard menu. Service was great. Space is nice but a bit crowded. Enjoyed the fried chicken coq au Vin, a signature dish. I know critics have raved about this place but I just didn't think it was anything special. Decent prices for a decent dinner.

Food was really average. No idea why the beef tartare had crunchy flakes in it, and the confit duck was tough. The bouillabaisse was inedible, and the choucroutte really disappointing - the pieces of meat were small and really nothing that special. The cheese platter were three thin slices of cheese you could almost see through them. Only highlight was the spicy lamb sausage - definitely recommended. Service could also be improved - felt rushed and not attentive at all.
Good food and good drink. Great value for Restaurant Week.

Ouff we were really looking forward to our dinner here but the service and food were awful. Avoid this place! The beef tartare was average, avoid the bouillabaisse and the pork in 8 ways was average. The cheese selection is miserly, the toffee desert was fine but nothing special. The profiteroles and key lime pie were strong. However, the service was terrible. Ten minutes late in being seated, despite a reservation, with no acknowledgement, plates being taken before they were finished, delays in serving bread and an attempt at charging for a higher priced wine than was served. This place really needs to up its game. Service at Zatinya Miles better, a little extra invested at Floriana or Zaytinya is well worth the cost.

Disappointed compared to my first visit. Waffles were dry and brittle; chicken had more breading than meat; waitress never checked up after serving food, not even to refill water. I’ll be back, I think, but I wouldn’t bring a friend here. The stars given are solely for the decor.

Convivial is a true hidden gem of a spot in Shaw. Run by the same group that has Mintwood, the standard of service is just as high as the other venture. Sunday night is all night happy hour with ~$10 burger, amazing small plates, and affordable cocktails. Their fried chicken (coq au vin) for $19 is without a doubt life changing. Brunch is top to bottom delicious. Start with a cinnamon roll or two for the table and try one of their creative options with edible flowers.
A bit pretentious but mostly tasty food. Don't bother with the omlette.
We were so pleased with the (birthday) dinner that we ended up coming back for brunch the next day! Great atmosphere, friendly staff, and delicious food.

The ambiance gets four stars, including the bar area which looked cool. Friendly, attentive staff. I give the food three stars relative to DC's five-star worthy restaurants. So still a decent rating, although for the price I'd hoped for something more. I agree with the reviewers who say some of the food was over-salted. The menu was pretty meat-heavy, and the server (and website) weren't able to tell us where their meat comes from, so I assumed they don't ethically/locally source. All in all, I would say there are better restaurants which are less pricey even within the same neighborhood. Worth trying at least once to see if it's your scene, especially since so many people seem to love it!

Great atmosphere, very friendly service.  Menu is quite moderate and location is upscale.  The beer on tap are largely from Microbrews.  If you prefer simple food, this isn't the place for you but if you have a diverse palette, you will enjoy it.

The pickled rockfish and grilled daurade were the highlights of a fantastic meal. However, the leeks dijonnaise disappointed. Soggy leeks on a plate could not be vindicated by the egg, breadcrumb, and caper topping. If you love yourself (and sugar), order the sticky toffee pudding. Our table literally gasped with delight at the first mouthful. Cherry on top: the ability to park in the Giant lot next door.
